where \(\bm{x}\) and \(\bm{y}\) are defined as \(\big{[}x_{n}^{\prime}\quad\cdots\quad x_{n-k+1}^{\prime}\big{]}^{T}\) and \(\big{[}x_{i-1}^{\prime}\quad\cdots\quad x_{i-k}^{\prime}\big{]}^{T}\) respectively, and \(\bm{M}_{n,i}^{\times}\) has rank at most that of \(\bm{M}_{n}^{(L-1)}\), which is \(2^{L-1}\). In particular, if \(2^{L-1}\leq k-2\), by Lemma 2 the proof concludes. 

### The general case: Transformers with \(H_{\ell}\) heads in layer \(\ell\): Proof of Theorem 6

The \(h^{\text{th}}\) head of the first layer of the attention-only transformer learns patterns of the form,

\[\widehat{\bm{x}}_{n}^{(1,h)} =\sum_{i\in n}\operatorname{att}_{n,i}^{(1,h)}\bm{W}_{V}^{(1,h)} \texttt{Emb}(x_{i})+\sum_{i\in n}\bm{W}_{V}^{(1,h)}\bm{p}_{n-i}^{V,(1,h)}\] (109) \[=\sum_{i\in n}\operatorname{att}_{n,i}^{(1,h)}\left(\frac{\phi^{h }(0)+\phi^{h}(1)}{2}+x_{i}^{\prime}\cdot\frac{\phi^{h}(1)-\phi^{h}(0)}{2} \right)+\sum_{i\leq n}\bm{W}_{V}^{(1,h)}\bm{p}_{n-i}^{V,(1,h)}\] (110)

where the last equation assumes a binary input sequence, defines \(x_{i}^{\prime}=2x_{i}-1\) and uses the notation \(\phi^{h}(0)=\bm{W}_{V}^{(1,h)}\texttt{Emb}(0)\) and \(\phi^{h}(1)=\bm{W}_{V}^{(1,h)}\texttt{Emb}(1)\). We can further rewrite this as,

\[\widehat{\bm{x}}_{n}^{(1,h)}=\bm{m}_{n}^{(1,h)}+\bm{M}_{n}^{(1,h)}\bm{x}_{1:T}\] (111)

where each \(\bm{M}_{n}^{(1,h)}\in\mathbb{R}^{d\times T}\) is rank \(1\) and applies a causal mask on the inputs \(x_{i}\) for \(i>n\). Recall that the output of the first attention layer applies a projection matrix on the concatentation of \(\widehat{\bm{x}}_{n}^{(1,h)}\) across \(h\in[H_{1}]\) and then adds a residual connection. The output can be written down as,

\[\widehat{\bm{x}}_{n}^{(2)}=\texttt{Emb}(x_{n})+\bm{W}_{O}^{(1)}\begin{bmatrix} \bm{m}_{n}^{(1,1)}\\ \vdots\\ \bm{m}_{n}^{(1,H_{1})}\end{bmatrix}+\bm{W}_{O}^{(1)}\begin{bmatrix}\bm{M}_{n}^ {(1,1)}\\ \vdots\\ \bm{M}_{n}^{(1,H_{1})}\end{bmatrix}\bm{x}_{1:T}\] (112)\[=\bm{m}_{n}^{(1)}+\bm{M}_{n}^{(1)}\bm{x}_{1:T},\] (113)

where,

\[\bm{M}_{n}^{(1)} =\left(\frac{\mathtt{Emb}(1)+\mathtt{Emb}(0)}{2}\right)e_{n}^{T}+ \bm{W}_{O}^{(1)}\begin{bmatrix}\bm{M}_{n}^{(1,1)}\\ \vdots\\ \bm{M}_{n}^{(1,H_{1})}\end{bmatrix},\text{ and,}\] (114) \[\bm{m}_{n}^{(1)} =\left(\frac{\mathtt{Emb}(1)-\mathtt{Emb}(0)}{2}\right)+\bm{W}_{O }^{(1)}\begin{bmatrix}\bm{m}_{n}^{(1,1)}\\ \vdots\\ \bm{m}_{n}^{(1,H_{1})}\end{bmatrix}\] (115)

Notice that the rank of the matrix \(\bm{M}_{n}^{(1)}\) is at most \(H_{1}+1\). This is because the concatenation operation can increase the rank at most additively, and since each of the \(\bm{M}_{n}^{(1,1)}\) matrices are rank at most \(1\).

Following through the proof in Appendix E.2 for the \(L\)-layer case, we can prove inductively that at any layer \(\ell\), the output looks like,

\[\bm{x}_{n}^{(\ell)}=\bm{m}_{n}^{(\ell)}+\bm{M}_{n}^{(\ell)}\bm{x}_{1:T}\] (116)

where the rank of \(\bm{M}_{n}^{(\ell)}\) is \(\prod_{i=1}^{\ell}(H_{i}+1)\). Invoking Lemma 2, if \(\prod_{i=1}^{L-1}(H_{i}+1)\leq k-2\), the attention-only transformer cannot realize a \(k^{\text{th}}\)-order induction head at layer \(L\).

